This paper discusses the representation power of graph neural networks (GNNs) and their limitations in distinguishing non-isomorphic graphs. Therefore, it is likely to belong to the sub-categories of machine learning (cs.LG), artificial intelligence (cs.AI), data structures and algorithms (cs.DS), neural and evolutionary computing (cs.NE), and social and information networks (cs.SI).
